-- Japanese Stock Futures Advance on Currency While Australian Shares Decline
-- B y   N o r i e   K u b o y a m a   a n d   T o s h i r o   H a s e g a w a
-- 2010-11-09T23:25:54Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-09/japanese-stock-futures-gain-on-weaker-yen-australian-shares-drop-on-gold.html
Japanese  stock   futures  gained as the
dollar strengthened to a two-week high against the yen, boosting
the outlook for export earnings, and Australian shares declined
after gold prices dropped from a record.  American depositary receipts of  Canon Inc. , a Japanese
camera maker that gets about 80 percent of its revenue from
overseas, advanced 0.3 percent from the closing share price in
Tokyo. Those of Nissan Motor Co., a carmaker that earns about a
third of its sales from North America, rose 0.5 percent.
Newcrest Mining Ltd., Australia’s biggest gold producer, sank
2.1 percent today in Sydney.  Futures on Japan’s Nikkei 225 Stock Average expiring in
December closed at 9,730 in Chicago yesterday, compared with
9,690 in Osaka, Japan. They were bid in the pre-market at 9,730
in Osaka at 8:05 a.m. local time today. Australia’s S&P/ASX 200
Index fell 0.1 percent today. New Zealand’s NZX 50 Index was
little changed in Wellington.  Futures on the  Standard & Poor’s 500 Index  were little
changed today. The index slid 0.8 percent yesterday, the most in
three weeks, as financial and raw-materials companies declined.  The dollar appreciated to as much as 81.97 yen about 5:50
a.m. in Tokyo, the strongest level since Oct. 27, boosting the
value of overseas income at Japanese companies when converted
into their home currency.  Gold futures dropped in after-hours trading in New York
after settling at a record high of $1,410.10 an ounce yesterday.
Crude oil for December delivery fell 0.4 percent to settle at
$86.72 a barrel in New York yesterday, the first drop in seven
days. During the day it rose to $87.63, the highest price since
October 2008.  Metals, Valuations  The London Metal Exchange Index of prices for six
industrial metals including copper and aluminum jumped 2.4
percent yesterday to the highest level since May 2008.  The  MSCI Asia Pacific Index  increased 12 percent this year
to yesterday, compared with gains of 8.8 percent by the S&P 500
and 7.7 percent by the Stoxx Europe 600 Index. Stocks in the
Asian benchmark are valued at 14.7 times estimated earnings on
average, compared with 14.3 times for the S&P 500 and 12.4 times
for the Stoxx 600.  To contact the reporters for this story:
